2 Therefore Cicero rightly says, that it is atrocious to break that saith which holds life together3 the holiest qood of the human beart, as Seneca speaks. And this, the supreme rulers of mankind ought to be more eareful of preserving, in proportion as they have more impunity for their violations of it : so that if saith be taken away, they will be like wild beasts, whose strength is an object of general horror. And in other parts of its sphere, justice has often somewhat that is obscure3 but the bond of good saith is manifest of itself, and indeed is used to remove obscurity from all other matters.
